\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asking an economist to describe the economic history in one picture, it
 would be a graph of an income/capita vs.
 time - not changing until the 19th century, when there was a change from
 stagnation to a sustained economic growth.
 We know that from (economic) historians - looking at books, analyzing wages,
 real incomes, etc.
 Once there are written records, we can make conclusions, though not very
 accurately but quite precise, regarding the economy in the past.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Going further back - archaeologists look at skeletons to learn about the
 quality of life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interesting thing is: looking up to the industrial revolution, the income
 is quite stable (there are small fluctuations), but it converges to an
 extreme poverty (>90% throughout most of history, <10% today), short life
 expentancy, high child mortality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, to answer questions about the difference between rich and poor
 countries today - looking at our history is helpful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking back at the hunters-gatherers society - the had some innovations,
 but they did not translate to an increase in qualty of life.
 Despite being productive, people did not begin to live better.
 Neither by introduction of farming, nor by domestication of some animals
 - the quality of life did not increase, and income per capita did not go
 up.
