\begin_layout Subsection
Sustained Growth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A sustained economic growth is explained by an accumulation of productivity
 factors and technological innovations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stagnation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Why for tens of thousands of years people didn't become richer? The Malthusian
 poverty trap (Thomas Malthus) states that population growth follows income
 growth.
 Inome per capita has a positive effect on population growth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mechanism of the trap is that aggregate income grows, leading to population
 growth, thus the income per capita doesn't grow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Malthus observed that low income leads to low fertility (positive check
 and preventative check).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at the past - any innovation that increases productivity leads only
 to an increase of population (the income per capita increase is only temporary).
 Malthus predicted the same for the future - luckily, he was wrong, as humanity
 has managed to escape the Malthusian poverty trap.
\end_layout

