\begin_layout Section
The Solow Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to answer a very simple question.
 We saw a correlation between physical capital and income per worker.
 There is a positive feedback loop from capital to income, and back to capital.
 It leads to the question: could that loop lead to a sustained economic
 growth?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The model assumes a constant technology and a discrete time measure with
 production affected by labor and capital (
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}$
\end_inset

) and a single good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Starting with some level of capital per worker, more capital today has a
 positive effect on the capital 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tomorrow
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but there is also a nefgative effect of depreciation.
 Will the economy necessarily converege? Can we ensure the positive effect
 being stronger than the negative effect? - Analyze the model to answer
 that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume the labor supply is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{t+1}=(1+n)L_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capital supply is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{t+1}=S_{t}+(1-\delta)K_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}$
\end_inset

 is aggregate saving and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 is the depreciation rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $n+\delta>0$
\end_inset

: eventually the output of worker is deternined by the capital per worker.
 Anything that has a negative effect on the numerator reduces it.
 But the population growth might increase the denominator, which would reduce
 the output as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=F(K_{t},L_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that the first derivatives are positive, and the second derivatives
 are negative (diminishing marginal product).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming constant returns to scale:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda F(K_{t},L_{t})=F(\lambda K_{t},\lambda L_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
we can rewrite the function as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=L_{t}F(K_{t}/L_{t},1)\equiv L_{t}f(k_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at different countries, it is very hard to find any link between
 scale and productivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a micro level, there are economies of scale - but not at the aggregate
 level.
 There is no contradiction with having economies of scale within each factory/in
dustry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(0)=0$
\end_inset

 (there is no output without capital).
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(k_{t})>0$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f''(k_{t})<0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The output per capita as a function of capital per capita is a standard
 production function (diminishing marginal product).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since it is a constant return to scale function, we can derive with respect
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

, leading to the result:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(k_{t})-f'(k_{t})k_{t}=F_{L}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which is the competitive wage per worker (the output he produces, net of
 the capital he uses).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F(K_{t},L_{t})=F_{K}K_{t}+F_{L}L_{t}$
\end_inset

, differentiating with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

, we find out that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{KL}>0$
\end_inset

.
 It means that the two factors of productions are 
\series bold
complementary
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregate saving is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{t}=sY_{t},\,\,s\in[0,1]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Saving is considered as a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mechanical
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 process, without any decision involved).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capital accumulation occurs by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{t+1}=S_{t}+(1-\delta)K_{t}=sL_{t}f(k_{t})+(1-\delta)K_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=\frac{K_{t+1}}{L_{t+1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t+1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t+1}=\frac{sf(k_{t})+(1-\delta)k_{t}}{1+n}\equiv\phi(k_{t})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capital (per worker) equals: (the savings per worker, plus the previous
 capital, net of depreciation), divided by the growth rate of the population
 (which dilutes the accumulation of the fators of production).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(k_{t})$
\end_inset

 uniquely determines 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t+1}$
\end_inset

, thus having a given 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{0}$
\end_inset

, all future values are known.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The properties of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 (derivatives) are similar to those of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Notice that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
lim_{k_{t}\rightarrow\infty}\phi'(k_{t})=\frac{1-\delta}{1+n}\in[0,1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The economy grows if and only if the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(k_{t})$
\end_inset

 function graph lies above the 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whenever the economy starts, it would always converge, and sustainable growth
 can't be maintained by the positive feedback loop described above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Economically we learn from this model that there is no growth in the steady
 state possible.
 More than capital accumulation is needed (e.g innovation, human capital).
 A steady state would be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{k}=\phi(\bar{k})=\frac{sf(\bar{k})+(1-\delta)\bar{k}}{1+n}\Rightarrow(n+\delta)\bar{k}=sf(\bar{k})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the steady state, the capital per worker equals the effective depreciation
 (taking into account the population growth).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 2 steady states: 0 (which is unstable) and a stable 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{k}>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

